      "name": "What happens to my depreciation claims when I sell an investment property in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "When you sell a residential investment property, the plant and equipment items you have been depreciating (such as hot water systems, carpets, dishwashers, and air conditioning units) may be subject to a balancing adjustment at sale. If the sale price attributed to those items exceeds their remaining tax value, the difference is treated as assessable income, not a capital gain. Capital works deductions (the building structure itself) are not subject to a balancing adjustment, but the buyer may use your schedule to calculate their own future deductions. Your accountant should model your approximate tax position before you list."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Should I give the buyer my depreciation schedule when selling an investment property?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes, and it is increasingly expected. An up-to-date depreciation schedule from a recognised quantity surveyor is a genuine asset for the buyer, as it documents the capital works deductions available to them going forward based on the original construction cost. Buyers purchasing an investment property will either ask for it or factor the cost of obtaining a new one into their decision. Including it in your data room or offering it as part of the sale reflects positively on your disclosure standards and can support your negotiating position."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Does the capital gains tax calculation change because I claimed depreciation?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Depreciation claims do not directly reduce your cost base for capital gains tax purposes on residential property sold after 7 December 2010. However, for plant and equipment items, a balancing adjustment applies separately from the CGT calculation. The interaction between depreciation recapture, the CGT discount, and any other tax considerations specific to your situation means you should work through your tax position with a qualified accountant or tax adviser before making decisions about timing or pricing your sale."
      }
    }
  ]
